<br>
I used to alternate between a staff of withering (for melee and stunning) with a rod of insidious glamour (for mezzing) and secondary holding a crude stein and sarnak ceremonial dagger in ranged slot. <br>
<br>
199 INT, 201 with brilliance, charisma (shaman buff), &amp; equipment (an insidious halo is a wonderful piece of equipment btw). I've noticed that I can mez Reds in the Plane of Fear with 201 CHA (which I've never been able to do before).<br>
<br>
It depends what my role is, generally I am seen circling at ground zero within melee range (unless facing a dread lord or tentacle terror, in which case I'm &quot;just&quot; out of combat range since I HATE getting dispelled). <br>
<br>
You'll notice your tactical strategies change as you progress in levels, get to know your group and what they are capable of. Make friends with EVERYBODY.<br>
<br>
*Warriors to keep an eye on your health to taunt creatures that will no doubt aggro you when you attempt crowd control.<br>
*Clerics to heal you and buff you. Carry around extra reagents, clerics and enchanters use the same reagents for different spells. At lower levels it is Cats Eye Agate and Bloodstones. At higher levels, Jasper and Peridots are a necessary evil for symbol and rune. (the only way enchanters can be effective combat controllers is with clerical buffs stacked with 'chanter buffs). <br>
*Shaman to perform secondary buffing duties or as secondary or emergency healer. (They get alacrity at higher levels to, and sow helps you run from nasties). Their Charisma buffs give more CHA than enchanter buffs (until level 49).<br>
*Druids to to buff you, serve as a backup healer to you in case cleric cannot or evacuate you to a druid-neutral location in case of emergency.<br>
<br>
Solonel N'Xairas<br>
---<br>
Combat Ground Traffic Controller<br>
Ministry of the Spurned, Neriak <br>
